{
  "text": "ble into a tetrameric structure [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . A notable exception to this rule of assembly is a group of ten \"silent\" or \"regulatory\" subunits discovered in mammals, Kv5.1, , that are self-incompatible and thus not able to form homotetramers, but can form functional heteromeric channels with novel biophysical properties when coexpressed with Kv2.1 or Kv2.2 [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] Salinas et al., 1997a,b; [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . While the names of these channels imply that they belong to distinct gene subfamilies, phylogenetic analysis places them within the Kv2 subfamily [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , thus preserving the principle of subfamily-specific assembly. In the absence of Kv2.1, Kv6.4 regulatory subunits do not assemble into tetramers and do not traffic to the plasma membrane [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Mammalian regulatory subunit T1s also do not oligomerize in vitro, suggesting T1 self-incompatibility plays a significant role in generation of the self-incompatible regulatory subunit phenotype [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] .",
